Data Preparation
a. Build your model dataset through three sequential joins:

Filter annual to Lees Ferry; rename total_flow to lees_flow
Join annual Glenwood Springs flow (site 09085000); rename to glenwood_flow
Join the dominant season at Lees Ferry per water year — the season with the highest total discharge
Log-transform both flow variables







Tip



The dominant season join: filter your seasonal summary to Lees Ferry, then within each water year select the season with the highest total flow: Hint: produce a single-row-per-year table by selecting Lees Ferry annual flows, left-joining Glenwood annual flows by water_year, joining the dominant season for Lees Ferry, and log-transforming the flow columns for modeling.
This is your fourth join. Verify: the final dataset should have ~44 rows, one per water year.




Code
lees_annual &lt;- annual_data |&gt; 
  filter(water_year &lt; 2024) |&gt;
  filter(site_no == "09380000") |&gt; 
  select(water_year, lees_flow = total_q)

glenwood_annual &lt;- annual_data |&gt; 
  filter(water_year &lt; 2024) |&gt;
  filter(site_no == "09085000") |&gt; 
  select(water_year, glenwood_flow = total_q)

lees_glenwood_annual &lt;- lees_annual |&gt; 
  left_join(glenwood_annual, by = "water_year")

nrow(lees_glenwood_annual == nrow(lees_annual))


