4.1 Quantify the Zone
Using your dist_to_border column, calculate:

How many cities fall within the 100-mile zone?
What is the total population living in cities within the zone?
What percentage of the total US city population does this represent?
Does your result match the ACLU’s published estimate?

Present your findings as a formatted flextable.






Tip



Filter to cities within 160 km, drop geometry if needed, then summarize: count rows (n()), sum population, and compute the percentage relative to total city population. You will need to reference total city population across the entire dataset, not just filtered rows — plan your calculation carefully.




Code
cities_in_zone &lt;- cities |&gt;
  drop_units() |&gt;
  filter(dist_to_border &lt; 160)

zone_summary &lt;- cities_in_zone |&gt;
  st_drop_geometry() |&gt;
  summarize(num_city_zone = nrow(cities_in_zone),
            population_in_zone = sum(population),
            total_population = sum(cities$population),
            percentage_in_zone = population_in_zone / total_population * 100) |&gt;
  select(-total_population)

zone_summary |&gt;
  flextable() |&gt;
  set_header_labels(
    num_city_zone = "Number of Cities in Zone",
    population_in_zone = "Population in Zone",
    percentage_in_zone = "Percentage of Total Population in Zone"
  ) |&gt;
  set_caption(paste0("Summary of U.S. Cities within the 100-mile Border Zone")) |&gt;
  autofit()


Number of Cities in ZonePopulation in ZonePercentage of Total Population in Zone13,363258,047,45465.24422


In 2–3 sentences: (1) report the percentage and compare it to the ACLU’s estimate, (2) explain why the result might be higher than many people expect given the geography of the US, (3) name one scenario where a water resources professional might need to navigate federal jurisdictional boundaries in a similar way — where a regulatory zone defined by distance from a physical boundary changes what analysis or permitting is required.

The ACLU gragphic denotes that 2/3 of the U.S. population live within this zone, which matches our estimate of 66.5%. This result might be higher than many people expect because most people think of the U.S.-Mexico border, even though the 100-mile zone encompasses coastal areas and the Canadian border. A water resources professional might need to navigate federal jurisdictional boundaries when working on projects that involve water bodies that cross national borders, such as with the Rio Grande or the Great Lakes.

4.3 Most Populous City per State in the Zone
Repeat the map from 4.2, but instead of the 10 most populous overall, label the most populous city in each state that falls within the zone.






Tip



filter(cities, as.numeric(dist_to_border) &lt; 160) |&gt;
  group_by(state_name) |&gt;
  slice_max(population, n = 1)




Code
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = states, fill = "grey", color = "white") +
  geom_sf(data = cities_in_zone, aes(geometry = geometry, color = dist_to_border), size = 1) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "darkred", high = "orange") +
  labs(title = "U.S. Cities within the 100-mile Border Zone",
       x = "Longitude",
       y = "Latitude",
       color = "Distance to Border (km)",
       caption = "Labelled cities are the most polpulous per state that falls within the zone") +
  ggrepel::geom_label_repel(
    data = cities_in_zone |&gt;
      group_by(state_name) |&gt;
      slice_max(population, n = 1),
    aes(geometry = geometry, label = city),
    stat = "sf_coordinates",
    size = 3
  )









Code
most_pop &lt;- cities |&gt;
  filter(state_name  %in% cities_in_zone$state_name) |&gt;
  group_by(state_name) |&gt;
  slice_max(population, n = 1) |&gt;
  st_drop_geometry() |&gt;
  select(state_name, city)

zone_pop &lt;- cities_in_zone |&gt;
  group_by(state_name) |&gt;
  slice_max(population, n = 1) |&gt;
  st_drop_geometry() |&gt;
  select(state_name, city)

diff_pop &lt;- setdiff(most_pop$city, zone_pop$city)


In 2–3 sentences: (1) how many states have at least one city in the zone? (2) Are there states where the most populous city is NOT in the zone — what does that tell you about that state’s geography? (3) How might the jurisdictional boundary created by this rule create challenges for environmental monitoring programs that cross state or national boundaries?

There are 35 states that have at least one city in the zone. Out of these 35 states, 13 have their most populous city outside of the zone. This tells us that certain staes may have more reliable water sources away from the zone. For example, Birmingham, AL is near the Coosa River, which is a major water source for the state, and is outside of the zone. The jurisdictional boundary may limit the ability of agencies to collect data or enforce regulations in certain areas, particularly those that are close to the border since jurisdictional authority may be limited to organizations outside of the Department of Homeland security.
